Certainly the Elder Gods aspect is an interesting new angle for a paranormal romance, but I

01:32.520 --> 01:35.760
feel that the characters are still lacking unique and dynamic voices.

01:35.760 --> 01:38.560
At present, they appear to be rather one dimensional.

01:38.560 --> 01:42.000
As a result, I fear this manuscript does not altogether work for me.

01:42.000 --> 01:45.360
Please remember that reactions to fiction are entirely subjective, so we recommend that

01:45.360 --> 01:48.200
you try some other agents.

01:48.200 --> 01:49.680
That was really nice of her.

01:49.680 --> 01:50.680
That was very nice of her.

01:50.680 --> 01:54.080
It's almost like she was in on the joke.

01:54.080 --> 02:01.480
This is a really good example of the nicest, most helpful rejection letter you could possibly,

02:01.480 --> 02:02.480
possibly hope for.

02:02.480 --> 02:09.680
So yeah, this can go up on our wall of proud.

02:09.680 --> 02:18.880
We got another rejection that was unfortunately not on a lovely printout with a company letterhead.

02:18.880 --> 02:22.640
First off, it was the agent's assistant, and it was just like, sorry, this isn't for me.

02:22.640 --> 02:24.000
Better luck next time.

02:24.000 --> 02:28.880
Which seems to be the more common form of rejection.

02:28.880 --> 02:29.880
So short.

02:29.880 --> 02:30.880
Short.

02:30.880 --> 02:31.880
Yeah.

02:31.880 --> 02:37.360
And I gotta be honest, I'm finding that even though it is like, the query is ridiculous,

02:37.360 --> 02:43.400
and we will read it, not this episode, but another one, it's still kind of nerve-wracking

02:43.400 --> 02:46.400
and it just kind of hurts your feelings, you know?

02:46.400 --> 02:51.120
What do you mean you're injecting our magnum opus of Cthulian love?

02:51.600 --> 02:53.600
Do you know how many people it took to make this?

02:53.600 --> 02:59.240
I feel like it's in the thousands by now.

02:59.240 --> 03:07.840
But with these two rejections from literary agencies, I should also bring up the fact

03:07.840 --> 03:15.160
that we did get some interest from an actual publisher, and this was kind of completely

03:15.160 --> 03:16.160
out of the blue.

03:16.160 --> 03:17.600
This was not something I reached out for.

03:17.600 --> 03:18.600
Someone messaged me.

03:18.600 --> 03:23.240
I'm not going to mention the publisher by name, but it's a small, independent publisher

03:23.240 --> 03:29.280
that specializes in science fiction, and one of their associate editors contacted me and

03:29.280 --> 03:33.200
said, hey, I've been watching the show, maybe you want to send us your manuscript and see

03:33.200 --> 03:36.960
if we might like to do something with it.

03:36.960 --> 03:44.000
And so that brought up an interesting sort of dilemma, since we were sort of going on

03:44.000 --> 03:48.480
the assumption that we were going to get rejected from everything because it's ridiculous.

03:48.480 --> 03:53.520
And then we were going to self-publish it and continue this ruse of this fake author

03:53.520 --> 04:00.080
who lives in Truttwood, Ohio with her five children, Matt A., Matt B., Allison, Josh,

04:00.080 --> 04:02.640
and Mary Ann.

04:02.640 --> 04:10.840
And now it's like, well, this brings up an interesting little dilemma.

04:10.840 --> 04:17.280
And that I think a lot of authors are struggling with right now, which is the question of traditional

04:17.280 --> 04:22.920
publishing through an actual publisher versus self-publishing, which is easier now than

04:22.920 --> 04:30.480
it has ever been in all of the history of the publishing.

04:30.480 --> 04:37.280
So traditional publishing through a publisher, publishing house, agents probably involved.

04:37.280 --> 04:44.040
Well, with those, there's often, what, the cash advance, there's people to actually help

04:44.040 --> 04:49.640
you edit your novel, make it the best it can be in theory.

04:49.640 --> 04:55.200
And also some marketing that I would think would go in it as well.

04:55.200 --> 04:59.040
It kind of exists on a spectrum.

04:59.040 --> 05:03.240
There are, I think the most common one is you publish with a traditional publisher and

05:03.240 --> 05:08.360
they give you a cash advance and then after a certain amount of successful sales you start

05:08.360 --> 05:10.640
to get residuals.

05:10.640 --> 05:15.360
There are some, especially newer digital imprints that have no cash advance.

05:15.360 --> 05:20.800
There are some that are residual only.

05:20.800 --> 05:27.000
It's like a wide spectrum that kind of varies from the traditional Stephanie Meyer gets

05:27.000 --> 05:31.680
an agent, agent finds a publisher, they publish it, she gets a seven-figure advance, I'm not

05:31.680 --> 05:32.680
kidding.

05:32.680 --> 05:33.680
Six-figure.

05:33.680 --> 05:36.680
She was six-figure, not seven-figure, sorry.

05:37.240 --> 05:40.640
But she apparently did get a six-figure advance for the Twilight series.

05:40.640 --> 05:43.520
This does not happen anymore.

05:43.520 --> 05:47.640
And then, of course, there's self-publishing.

05:47.640 --> 05:56.960
Which is completely changing the paradigm, especially in light of our good friend E.L.

05:56.960 --> 05:57.960
James here.

05:57.960 --> 06:05.240
There are a lot of authors that did kind of start in this genre that we are exploring

06:05.320 --> 06:07.320
slash parodying.

06:07.320 --> 06:08.800
Amanda Hawking is one.

06:08.800 --> 06:15.000
I'm not familiar, I haven't read any of her stuff but I know she was very popular in Amazon.

06:15.000 --> 06:18.000
Colleen Hawke?

06:18.000 --> 06:19.760
Hooke?

06:19.760 --> 06:23.760
So it is changing the paradigm a little bit but I think in terms of the actual publishing

06:23.760 --> 06:29.200
industry these people are extreme outliers.

06:29.200 --> 06:36.000
The vast, vast, vast, vast, vast majority of people who self-publish will sell like

06:36.000 --> 06:38.920
three and a half copies.

06:38.920 --> 06:44.920
So the question is, what would be better for our Sarah Ellinson traditional publishing,

06:44.920 --> 06:52.200
and we're not assuming that this publisher will like her masterpiece, which we did design

06:52.200 --> 06:55.880
to be a very subtle parody.

06:55.880 --> 06:58.360
It's not like a Harvard blampoon, you know?

06:58.360 --> 07:01.280
Of course, there is a question of turnaround.

07:01.280 --> 07:02.280
Yeah, exactly.

07:02.280 --> 07:05.600
If we did go with a traditional publisher and if they did like it and they made us an

07:05.600 --> 07:11.040
offer it would take at least a year for the public to see the light of day because we

07:11.040 --> 07:16.760
have to do copy editing and then we have to do the early reviewers and the bookboggers

07:16.760 --> 07:22.480
and then it's because publishing is like, the film industry is like a greyhound, publishing

07:22.480 --> 07:26.320
is like a sloth on Xanax or something.

07:26.320 --> 07:28.920
Now I mean you made the mention before of E.L.

07:28.920 --> 07:35.600
James went very quickly from self-published to a smaller publishing company to Random

07:35.600 --> 07:36.600
House.

07:36.600 --> 07:41.680
Very fast turnaround and oh brother does it show.

07:41.680 --> 07:48.040
The phrase, floor the pedal to the metal is in the final manuscript.

07:48.040 --> 07:49.560
Floor the pedal to the metal, okay.

07:50.000 --> 07:53.680
It's like someone gave it one more run through and was like, done.

07:53.680 --> 07:55.240
Yeah, it's going to make us money, I don't care.

07:55.240 --> 07:56.240
And it worked.

07:56.240 --> 07:57.240
And it worked?

07:57.240 --> 07:58.240
Yeah, it worked.

